The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | The City Diary
                                                                                                            The City Diary
                Three dacoits, two of them Bangladeshis, were arrested in Burrabazar on Tuesday. They had assembled to loot a traders house. The trio  Hanif Mollah, 25, and Mohammad Ilahi, 21, of Bangladesh, and Mohammad Habibullah Gayen, 24, a resident of Baruipur in South 24-Parganas  were involved in several robberies in the city over the past few years, said Uma Shankar Ojha, the officer-in-charge of Burrabazar police station. Two choppers and a map of the area were found on the trio. The Bangladeshis had crossed over illegally, said the police.     Darshan Singh, 50, a resident of Kundu Lane in Bhowanipore, was run over by a Matador on Circus Avenue at 3.30pm on Tuesday. He was taken to SSKM Hospital, where doctors declared him brought dead. The driver of the van fled. The vehicle has been impounded.     Two associates of extortionist Sridhar were held in Chetla on Tuesday. The duo were identified as Sukumar Nandi and Biswajit Halder. Two improvised pistols were found on them.     A drug peddler, identified as Sheikh Babloo, 29, was arrested in Mominpore Lane on Tuesday. Thirteen grams of heroin was found on him. Police said Babloo had been operating in the area for months and used to supply drugs to high-profile clients.     The Mumbai Mail (via Gaya-Allahabad and via Patna) will have two additional coaches, including one AC three-tier coach, from Thursday. Eastern Railway officials said the train will have a total of 11 sleeper class coaches and two AC three-tier coaches after January 10.    South Eastern Railway has recorded 11.3 per cent rise in freight load from April to December 2007 against the same period in 2006. An official said on Tuesday that the railway loaded 80.5 million tonnes of freight between April and December last year, which is 8.2 million tonnes more than the corresponding period of 2006.             
